Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was registered, according to the EU's Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are down just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the American, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate. According to their discretion, the rate cut would favour rising commodity prices and the slight drop in unemployment the emergence of a spiral of inflation.
The ECB is eager to keep inflation below two per cent, or at least narrowly at the two-percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in a quandary: inflation must be "denied" in order to exclude later action.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in November in Germany reached a twelve-year record high; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The increase in food and energy prices is responsible for the rise in inflation in the eurozone.
MATIF wheat quotes rose 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in cooking oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil rose 52 percent this year - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly US$100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to decline to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup locates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably by early December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while approval for the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
Among party-loyal voters, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) face a fifth (20 percent) approval for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry hurdle: They come in the total population to two percent.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low point, overall economic sentiment has continued to deteriorate - never before has the proportion of those who judge the country's economic situation as "extremely bad" have been so high (41 per cent), while another 46 per cent consider it to be "pretty bad."
After more hopeful prospects in the spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about changing their financial situation.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only a tenth assumes an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents - a historic high - judged the prime minister's work to be "rather bad than right."
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the proportion of proponents for Viktor Orbán accounts for 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared to 27% distrust of the party leader of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of those who think that you could get to grips with the dissatisfaction with the prime minister even without a change of government.
After the unrest last October, 35% had still spoken out in favour of the government and the head of government, but today this share amounts to only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent responded that they would "certainly" participate, and another 20% would "likely" cast their vote.
By comparison, if the general election were to be held this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty," another 15% consider their participation "likely." Given these tendencies, the result of the referendum would be foreseeable.
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital daily allowance.
Transferred to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty", the shares of the opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would even be 81, 84, or 89 percent.
