In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals, which were due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the containment of the infections, according to the senior doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the János hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The bacterium, resistant to antibiotics, was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was already a similar infection here.
The injured man of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a short time later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been performed because of the bacterium, which is still in the patient's body.
To 10. December of this year, 1094 infections triggered by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System from hospitals, according to the senior doctor of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections triggered by multidrug-resistant pathogens were certainly registered in the hospitals, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by the MRSA, the staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in their nose without it causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if the agents are metered too high or improperly applied, the well-responsive bacteria produce antibiotic-resistants, which spread rapidly in the hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poorly functioning immune systems, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the hospital everyday life.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, so Timbor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wears rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," according to Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, patients are examined for MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Samples too rare
The majority of the infections triggered by MRSA in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for the containment of the origin or the spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and retirement homes, the hospitals should examine the admitted patients and immediately isolate MRSA-infected.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practiced as frequently.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this investigation on the part of the state health insurance company.
Most cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
On the part of the European Union, there are strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and clinical pictures.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations are necessary so that no resistance to the agent can form, but this directive is not always adhered to by hospitals.
Among the outpatients, or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Savings are made on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted by nursing staff from one patient to the other.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in the hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds narrowly lined up, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately in the financially less well-off hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that almost favor the development of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less frequent there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are adhered to, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control is causing huge costs for health insurance companies, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
After initial signs, the programme is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the development of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
Death-steering police chief was not drunk
In the case of the police chief of the XXII. District caused car accident with fatal outcome is now the official report.
