Another 400 million EUR for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) signed three loan agreements totalling 400 million EUR in Budapest on Friday. The money is to flow into education, transport and environmental protection infrastructure and the energy industry.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a 300 million EUR framework for the financing of transport and environmental protection projects implemented by grants from the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement for 100 million has already been signed earlier, the current agreement is about the use of the falling in love 200 million EUR.
The sum of 150 million EUR agreed in the loan agreement is also to be spent on the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of 300 million euros for this purpose for Hungary; the use of the remaining 150 million euros will be decided later in the context of the extension of the credit agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of 50 million euros, which will mainly flow into research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the subway line 4 was also discussed.
It was agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of the subway financing with the EU, the original contract and any modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects totalling EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest rates are EURIBOR-linked, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, commission-free.
Bulgaria, the EU real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe looks closely at the Balkan state, which was rarely mentioned in the past.
What, where, and who buys on the still cheapest market of the EU, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis by the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most sought-after patch for property purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar are the racers, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik is also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country will sooner or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and the extremely favorable area of Russe, for example, also records more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - trading and office space offers the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive European golfer paradises, and thus attract tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already shopping on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who acquire real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking a change in their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle buy either revitalized properties around 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connection and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are very important, but also the proximity to a large city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group is making up business people who are investing with the goal of a medium to long-term increase in value.
Real estate in the capital, however, is constantly becoming more expensive, due to the ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the past five years there has been a price increase of 21 percent annually.
The price increase in property prices far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will come to an end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali roadmap, which defines the emission-reducing measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
A fierce debate is currently underway between developed and developing countries.
The U.S. has already signalled that it does not want to negotiate on concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether the industrialized countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on support for developing countries has also been reached.
The Adaptation Fund, which is subordinate to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be managed by a 16-member council, probably at the UN's Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be read in the "Piac és Profit."
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's effort to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured by the 1990 values), regardless of whether the "after 2012 agreement" is successfully achieved or not. The Union would even be prepared to commit to a 30 percent reduction, provided that other major industrialized countries in the world, or Developing countries are also prepared to fulfil their obligations to the best of their ability and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor emphasized that the objective of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed to a minus of 8%.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the years 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will certainly meet, as can be read in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The deployment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be ready within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction projects set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by a new, international emission reduction system, the importance of which the IPCC, the UN’s international Nobel Peace Prize-winning scientific climate change committee, also highlighted in its latest report.
This would delay the emission reduction, and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British Army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan for the purpose of increasing popularity on the video portal.
Initially, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of Taliban-led operations to the net since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The footage, shot with miniature cameras attached to helmets, is controlled at the airbase in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are put on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such shots, their "channel" being viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Foreign Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeepers (MNFIs) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of the foreign missions.
Propaganda published in this way is almost free of charge compared to conventional television advertisements, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message, since they confirm the justification of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored footage, also make it to the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are only talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Of the theatres of war in Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genus" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-scare simulation.
