More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
The League of Unions and the Hungarian Union Federation are forming their coordination committee on Friday for the strike of indefinite duration, which begins on Monday.
A large-scale protest meeting will be held on Saturday, with a work stoppage on Monday - on the day of the referendum on the health insurance law.
Strike-related, significant traffic obstructions are expected, as rail traffic is almost completely stopped, and the Budapest public transport companies (BKV) also strike until 13 o'clock.
Details of Monday's strike will be jointly announced on Friday afternoon by the League of Unions and the Union Federation.
It will also establish a LEAGUE - MOSZ strike committee responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
A protest-greater assembly will be held on Saturday, and from Monday, all organisations that have joined the strike will put down work for an indefinite period of time, unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike, which began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance law, was not defined.
If the National Council does not adopt the Health Insurance Act, the unions immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet to discuss how to proceed.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that it will only come to a vote on the health insurance law in the later evening hours, or even at midnight.
The strikes, which begin on Monday, will have to face significant traffic obstructions: the railway workers will put down their work for an indefinite period of time, in the morning the majority of public transport and more than half of the Volán companies will stand still.
