The Hungarian Medical Association is on strike nationwide alternately at various times, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organization of the SZEF, the Forum for Cooperation of the Unions, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraws the draft reform of health insurance and puts forward a new conception for social discourse.
The second claim concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
Claim number three is that the eligible professional groups will be given access to the early retirement system before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, has not accepted the offer made by the Ministry of Transport, which provides the sidelines and is now calling for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard raises state risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
The institute's "risk warning report" states, among other things: In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk represents the "intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at the provocation of such a dispute, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of the political leaders: "Persons of public life have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition".
It is suspected that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also thinks that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention on the part of the domestic and foreign media, "have significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially with regard to trust in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: Since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously on the upswing, so that since summer 2007 several organizations calling themselves "national self-defense association" have been founded.
"These groups have in common that they each define themselves as a civilian organization, while they openly brag about preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (catastrophe protection, national defense, order protection), citing the unfitness of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further: All this is done according to the method that seeks to disguise various political aspirations based on the political and party disenchantment of the population as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association thus do not merely serve to circumvent legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration with the court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As can be seen from the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard represent a risk-increasing factor for relations with the neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited in several neighboring states as a potential source of danger, so many ultra-nationalist politicians of certain neighboring countries see in the emergence of the Hungarian Guard the confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
All of this has implications for the region's political stability" - it said.
