Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, public holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of rescheduling the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year will give us fewer such days.
In the EU and in America, too, one understands otherwise by "holiday."
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and days off work.
Work-free days are usually church holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
We also celebrate New Year, for example: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are days off work - the latter alone so that the New Year's Eve releasers can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are the 15th. March, reminiscent of the revolution of 1848, and the 23rd. October, the commemoration of the 1956 revolution.
On 20. August will be the founding of the state, on 1. May the work celebrated, on 1 and 2. We remember our dead in November.
In addition, there are two holidays each for Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day postponement" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, should ultimately be processed, has been determined for many years by the Minister of Labour in its own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public servants and civil servants alike.
Excluded are only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on the holidays.
This year, the work regulations are only confused by the holidays at the end of the year: From the 24th. December the life in this country remains formally, since most for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve take time compensation, or the specially lifted holiday.
Next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or the end of the week, so there will be fewer reschedulings during the working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around Labor Day so that people can stay home for four days at a time.
Saturday, the 26th April will be a working day so that Friday, 2. May can be a rest day.
The second rescheduling hangs with the holiday on 23. October together: On Saturday, the 18th. October will be Friday, 24. October must be processed in advance.
However, the end of the year will be completely marked by the holidays, after from the 24. December everything is lying and standing still, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
