Cuba - the most beautiful island of the Caribbean
For visitors, it really is an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, that will be fulfilled if you only choose the right thing.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palm trees and all-inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in an abundant amount.
But only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place ever seen by a human eye.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spanish had robbed in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20. century.
One of the heads of the American Mafia, Lucky Luciano, built it, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (especially during Prohibition) was gladly seen and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were, among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, across the wide boulevards drove cars that were among the cult symbols of the 1950s of the past century.
Ernest Hemingway bought an estate in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
On the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana you can also leave your autograph.
At the bar at the Hotel Nacional, cocktails are available as you wish.
And the cult cars of the Fifties drive around Havana to this day, because the once imported Schigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
Although Havana, especially its oldest part, may have been heavily run down, nowhere can you find so many wonderful colonial sights in the vicinity as just here.
Other places are being cleaned out right now, for example Trinidad.
With regard to the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, it was given the green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, not only new hotels have been built in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a quirk that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane of remote plantations brought steam- and diesel-powered narrow-gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
The most significant places are not missed by the majority of Cuban visitors.
So you no longer have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail.
It should only be mentioned that in the already mentioned estate Hemingways there is a museum, whose visit should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on lime soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, through which also weathered rocky areas are covered by dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is cultivated.
In its final form, you can meet him when you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was shot there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Fame and wealth brought her the trade in slaves and sugar.
The wealth was embodied in the pretty beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has barely changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountains, is such a remote place that there was no road there that would have connected the area to the rest of the country in the 1950s.
This insulation helped ensure that it went unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was demolished, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as the beach Playa Ancón or the "Valley of Sugar Factories".
In the evening you should go to the Casa de la Música, which revives after the darkness, and where the music is not silent until the morning.
Baracoa
Some people in eastern Cuba describe this small town as the most beautiful on the island.
Certainly, this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading there from Guantánamo must overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape that is barely touched by human intervention.
Thanks to the unspoilt nature there, UNESCO included this eastern outpost of Cuba in its World Heritage register.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you show the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the journeys of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, several table mountains can be seen, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra Mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion, to which the descendants of slaves profess, about all this one could write many pages.
But as they say, look better with your own eyes.
