New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is simmering between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe being affected.
Most of Russia's natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are routed through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is being watched very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for the natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during talks," Ukraine's economy minister, Anatoli Kinakh, told Reuters news agency.
"Changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This subsequently led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which dramatically drove up prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas deposits, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The consequence is that Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS 'must control foreign workers'
The Scottish State Health Service must improve checks on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, a member of the control body said. outside
The recommendation of the main financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in connection with the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also raised concerns that the Scottish State Health Service has no precise expectations regarding the number of its foreign staff.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were carried out correctly at a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller examined personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road vehicle was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the suspected car bombing in the UK.
The State Health Service is expected to carry out checks in advance of the employment of foreign staff to ensure that they possess the skills, experience and authorizations required to work in the UK.
Although health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency does not have the competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The report of the principal auditor now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record extract, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, these have not been carried out routinely," the report noted.
Black said Scottish health authorities would follow their investigation guidelines before employment with a high measure, but added: "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information about the number of foreign health service workers is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations in advance of the employment of potential NHS staff would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report states that current pre-employment tests by the NHS Scotland are performing well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will deliver," he said.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign staff, the vast majority of whom have doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, also because the boards would have trouble identifying those employees who are on leave indefinitely.
The investigation further found that established control procedures of NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian have been predominantly adhered to.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidance on checks before the start of employment for foreign staff in the NHS.
Secretary of Health Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was a concern for me to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that best practices would be reflected in updated guidance on check-ups in the run-up to employment by all staff - including those from abroad - whose publication is planned next month.
