"Venus may be the devil's twin of the Earth, but it's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to the Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development, is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the early 1990s there was no probe specifically for the exploration of this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research, which is now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underlines the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet with the Earth are greater than initially thought," the Esa announces.
