The second-innermost planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, will be orbiting the sun in just under 225 days.
But it revolves much slower around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans but was lost on Venus into space.
