These aren't Warhol's boxes
Those who combine the terms Sweden and wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, in Sweden, fabricated wooden boxes cast dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue of works.
A large part of the ninety-four Brillo boxes of the "Type Stockholm" listed there are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" stoked doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968 a few months ago, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now comes to a sobering result: The six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén bequitted to the Moderna Museum in 1995 as a donation, are copies - and probably also the majority of the around
The prehistory is nested, a confusing concatenation of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the soap powder "Brillo."
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's consent - turned hundreds of Brillo boxes out of cardboard: These did not come (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not works of art, but their role models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museum.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at that time were rightly incorporated into the history of art and auction as authorized original Andy Warhol-Brillo boxes with the designation "Typ Stockholm".
Some of them have achieved more than 100 000 dollars at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only placed in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg produced.
At that point, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has examined not only the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, three of which were privately owned by the museum, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their pressboards were first primed and sanded, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint with a painter's roll without a primer was applied directly to the press chipboard - in addition, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, said in a statement: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibiting material."
Already in July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious accusations" made in the case of the soap powder boxes.
But since then, people have been shrouded in relentless silence.
